in javascript how do you save to and read back from localstorage

### Response:


To save data to the local storage in JavaScript, you can use the `localStorage` object that is available in all modern browsers. Here's an example of how to save a string value to the local storage:
```javascript
// Get the current date and time
var now = new Date();
var currentTime = now.toLocaleString();

// Set the expiration time for the data
var expirationTime = new Date(now.getFullYear(), now.getMonth() + 1, now.getDate());

// Check if the data is already in storage
if (localStorage.getItem('myData')) {
    // The data is already there, so update it
    localStorage.setItem('myData', currentTime);
} else {
    // The data is not there, so save it
    localStorage.setItem('myData', currentTime);
}
```
To read back the value from the storage, you can use the `getItem()` method:
```javascript
// Get the data from storage
var myData = localStorage.getItem('myData');
console.log(myData); // Outputs the saved date and time
``` 
Note that the data stored in the local storage is not encrypted or secure, so it's important to use this feature carefully.
